{
  "What is air resistance?": "",
  "The force that air exerts on a moving object, opposing its motion": "",
  "The gravitational pull that the Earth exerts on all objects": "",
  "The magnetic force between two metallic objects in the air": "",
  "The elastic force that springs exert on attached objects": "",
  "Air resistance is a friction-like force that air exerts on objects moving through it. It always opposes the direction of motion and increases as the object moves faster.": "",
  "What happens to air resistance as an object moves faster?": "",
  "Air resistance stays the same at all speeds": "",
  "Air resistance increases as speed increases": "",
  "Air resistance decreases as speed increases": "",
  "Air resistance disappears at high speeds": "",
  "Air resistance increases as speed increases. Faster objects push through more air molecules per second, creating a greater opposing force. This is why it feels windier when you run faster.": "",
  "Which factor does NOT affect the amount of air resistance on an object?": "",
  "The speed of the moving object through the air": "",
  "The cross-sectional area of the moving object": "",
  "The color of the moving object in the air": "",
  "The shape of the moving object through the air": "",
  "Air resistance depends on speed, cross-sectional area, shape, and air density. The color of the object does not affect how air flows around it, so it has no impact on air resistance.": "",
  "How does a larger cross-sectional area affect air resistance?": "",
  "It decreases air resistance on the object": "",
  "It has no effect on air resistance at all": "",
  "It eliminates air resistance entirely": "",
  "It increases air resistance on the object": "",
  "A larger cross-sectional area means the object pushes aside more air as it moves. This increases air resistance. A parachute works by having a very large area to maximize air resistance.": "",
  "Why do race cars have smooth, streamlined shapes?": "",
  "To reduce air resistance and go faster": "",
  "To increase air resistance for safety": "",
  "To increase their weight on the track": "",
  "To make them look more attractive overall": "",
  "Streamlined shapes allow air to flow smoothly around the car, reducing turbulence and air resistance. Less drag means the car can reach higher speeds using the same engine power.": "",
  "In which direction does air resistance act on a falling object?": "",
  "Downward, same as gravity pulls": "",
  "Sideways, perpendicular to falling": "",
  "Upward, opposite to the falling direction": "",
  "In no particular or set direction": "",
  "Air resistance always opposes the direction of motion. For a falling object moving downward, air resistance acts upward. This upward force slows the object's acceleration until it reaches terminal velocity.": "",
  "What is another common name for air resistance?": "",
  "Tension force": "",
  "Normal force": "",
  "Drag force": "",
  "Spring force": "",
  "Air resistance is commonly called drag or drag force. The term 'drag' is used because the force drags back on (opposes) the motion of objects moving through air or any fluid.": "",
  "Does air resistance exist in a vacuum (no air)?": "",
  "Yes, air resistance exists everywhere": "",
  "Yes, but it is much weaker in a vacuum": "",
  "No, there is no air resistance in a vacuum": "",
  "No, but gravity also disappears in vacuum": "",
  "Air resistance requires air molecules to push against the object. In a vacuum, there are no air molecules, so there is no air resistance. This is why objects in space can travel without slowing down.": "",
  "How does a parachute use air resistance to help a skydiver?": "",
  "It creates a large area that increases drag to slow the fall": "",
  "It reduces gravity so the skydiver weighs much less": "",
  "It pushes the skydiver upward using rocket propulsion": "",
  "It eliminates all forces acting on the falling skydiver": "",
  "A parachute has a very large surface area that catches air. This greatly increases air resistance (drag), slowing the skydiver's fall to a safe landing speed by balancing gravity at a much lower velocity.": "",
  "At higher altitudes where air is thinner, what happens to air resistance?": "",
  "Air resistance increases dramatically": "",
  "Air resistance stays exactly the same": "",
  "Air resistance decreases because air is less dense": "",
  "Air resistance reverses its direction": "",
  "At higher altitudes, the air is less dense (thinner), meaning there are fewer air molecules to push against moving objects. This reduces air resistance. Planes can fly faster at high altitudes for this reason.": "",
  "What is drag force?": "",
  "A resistance force that opposes motion through a fluid like air": "",
  "A force that only acts on objects that are completely at rest": "",
  "A force that increases the speed of objects moving forward": "",
  "A gravitational force that pulls all objects toward Earth": "",
  "Drag force is the resistance force that acts on an object moving through a fluid such as air or water. It always opposes the direction of motion and depends on speed, shape, area, and fluid density.": "",
  "What does 'streamlined' mean?": "",
  "Having a shape that minimizes air resistance": "",
  "Having a flat and boxy shape for extra room": "",
  "Being painted with stripes for high visibility": "",
  "Moving at a very slow and constant speed": "",
  "Streamlined means having a smooth, tapered shape designed to reduce air resistance. Air flows smoothly around streamlined objects with less turbulence. Birds, fish, and aircraft are all streamlined.": "",
  "What does 'turbulence' mean in the context of air resistance?": "",
  "Smooth, even airflow around an object in motion": "",
  "Chaotic, swirling air that increases drag force": "",
  "The absence of any air around the moving object": "",
  "The gravitational pull of air on the object": "",
  "Turbulence is chaotic, swirling air motion created behind a moving object. It increases drag significantly. Streamlined shapes reduce turbulence by allowing air to flow smoothly around the object.": "",
  "What does 'cross-sectional area' mean for air resistance?": "",
  "The front-facing area that pushes through the air": "",
  "The total surface area of the entire object": "",
  "The weight of the object in newtons or pounds": "",
  "The volume of air inside the moving object": "",
  "Cross-sectional area is the area of the object as seen from the front (the direction of motion). A larger front-facing area pushes against more air, creating more drag.": "",
  "What does 'terminal velocity' mean?": "",
  "The maximum constant speed when drag equals gravity": "",
  "The speed at which an object first begins to fall": "",
  "The speed of sound through the air at sea level": "",
  "The minimum speed needed to overcome air resistance": "",
  "Terminal velocity is the constant speed reached when drag force equals gravitational force. At this point, the net force is zero, acceleration stops, and the object falls at a steady speed.": "",
  "What does 'fluid' mean in physics when discussing drag?": "",
  "Only liquids like water and oil in containers": "",
  "Any substance that flows, including gases and liquids": "",
  "Only gases like oxygen and nitrogen in the air": "",
  "Solid materials that are very smooth and shiny": "",
  "In physics, a fluid is any substance that flows, which includes both liquids and gases. Air is a fluid, which is why objects experience drag when moving through it, just as they do in water.": "",
  "What is meant by 'aerodynamic'?": "",
  "Designed to move through air with minimal resistance": "",
  "Designed to be as heavy as possible for stability": "",
  "Designed to create maximum turbulence in the air": "",
  "Designed to float on water without sinking down": "",
  "Aerodynamic means designed to move through air efficiently with minimal resistance. Aerodynamic shapes are smooth and tapered, reducing drag. Cars, planes, and even cyclists' helmets are made aerodynamic.": "",
  "What does 'air density' mean in the context of drag?": "",
  "How tightly packed the air molecules are in a space": "",
  "The temperature of the air at a given location": "",
  "The speed at which wind blows across a surface": "",
  "The color of the sky on a clear day outdoors": "",
  "Air density is the mass of air per unit volume. Denser air has more molecules packed into a space, creating more resistance when objects move through it. Air is denser at sea level than at high altitudes.": "",
  "What does 'drag coefficient' mean?": "",
  "A number describing how much drag a shape creates": "",
  "The maximum speed an object can travel through air": "",
  "The weight of the air around a moving object": "",
  "The direction in which drag pushes on an object": "",
  "The drag coefficient is a dimensionless number that represents how much drag a particular shape produces. A lower drag coefficient means less air resistance. A teardrop shape has a very low drag coefficient.": "",
  "What does 'wind resistance' mean?": "",
  "The gravitational force acting on wind itself": "",
  "The force of air pushing against a moving object": "",
  "The speed at which wind blows from one direction": "",
  "The temperature change caused by moving wind": "",
  "Wind resistance is another term for air resistance or drag. It is the force air exerts on a moving object, opposing its motion. The term is often used in everyday language for the same concept as drag.": "",
  "A cyclist crouches low on a bike instead of sitting upright. How does this affect air resistance?": "",
  "It increases air resistance on the cyclist": "",
  "It decreases air resistance on the cyclist": "",
  "It makes gravity pull harder on the cyclist": "",
  "Crouching low reduces the cyclist's cross-sectional area (the front-facing area that hits the air). A smaller area means less air is pushed aside, reducing drag and allowing the cyclist to go faster.": "",
  "Why does a flat piece of cardboard fall more slowly than a ball of the same mass?": "",
  "The cardboard has a larger area creating more air resistance": "",
  "The ball weighs more than the flat cardboard piece": "",
  "Gravity pulls harder on the ball than the cardboard": "",
  "The cardboard is lighter than the ball altogether": "",
  "The flat cardboard has a much larger cross-sectional area, which creates more air resistance. It reaches a lower terminal velocity and falls more slowly. The ball has less area and higher terminal velocity.": "",
  "A skydiver spreads out like a starfish versus diving headfirst. In which position is air resistance greater?": "",
  "Diving headfirst position creates more drag": "",
  "Both positions have exactly the same drag": "",
  "Spread out starfish position creates more drag": "",
  "Neither position experiences any drag at all": "",
  "The spread-out position has a much larger cross-sectional area facing the airflow, which creates more air resistance. Skydivers use this to control their descent speed, switching between spread and tucked positions.": "",
  "A truck and a sports car drive at the same speed. Which likely experiences more air resistance?": "",
  "The sports car because it is faster": "",
  "Both experience exactly the same drag": "",
  "Neither vehicle experiences any drag": "",
  "The truck because it is larger and boxier": "",
  "At the same speed, the truck experiences more air resistance because it has a larger cross-sectional area and a less streamlined (more boxy) shape. The sports car is designed with a sleek shape to minimize drag.": "",
  "Why do birds tuck their wings close to their body when diving?": "",
  "To reduce their cross-sectional area and minimize drag": "",
  "To increase their air resistance for a slow dive": "",
  "To make themselves heavier for the diving motion": "",
  "To protect their feathers from the wind force": "",
  "Tucking wings reduces the bird's cross-sectional area, minimizing air resistance. This allows the bird to dive faster, reaching speeds that would be impossible with wings spread out creating more drag.": "",
  "A golf ball has dimples on its surface. How do these affect air resistance?": "",
  "They increase air resistance making the ball fly less far": "",
  "They reduce drag by controlling airflow around the ball": "",
  "They have no effect on how the ball flies through air": "",
  "They make the ball heavier so it flies in a straight line": "",
  "Golf ball dimples actually reduce drag by creating a thin layer of turbulence close to the surface. This helps air flow around the ball more smoothly overall, reducing the wake behind it and decreasing total drag.": "",
  "An airplane flies from a low altitude to a very high altitude. What happens to the drag on the plane?": "",
  "Drag increases because the plane is going higher up": "",
  "Drag stays exactly the same regardless of altitude": "",
  "Drag reverses direction and pushes the plane forward": "",
  "Drag decreases because air is thinner at high altitude": "",
  "At higher altitudes, air is less dense (thinner). Fewer air molecules means less resistance against the plane. This is one reason commercial jets cruise at high altitudes - less drag means better fuel efficiency.": "",
  "A student drops two identical balls from the same height, one on Earth and one on the Moon (no atmosphere). Which hits the ground with less air resistance?": "",
  "The ball dropped on Earth due to thicker air": "",
  "Both experience the exact same air resistance": "",
  "The Moon ball has zero air resistance since there is no air": "",
  "The Earth ball has zero air resistance at that height": "",
  "The Moon has no atmosphere, so there is no air resistance there at all. The ball on the Moon experiences zero drag and is in true free fall. The ball on Earth experiences air resistance that increases as it speeds up.": "",
  "A swimmer moves through water. Is water resistance generally stronger or weaker than air resistance at the same speed?": "",
  "Water resistance is much weaker than air resistance": "",
  "Water resistance is much stronger than air resistance": "",
  "They are exactly equal at the same speed of motion": "",
  "There is no resistance when moving through water": "",
  "Water is much denser than air, so water resistance (drag) is much greater than air resistance at the same speed. This is why swimming feels much harder than running at similar speeds.": "",
  "A delivery company tests two box shapes for truck cargo: a flat-front box and a rounded-front box. Which creates less drag at highway speeds?": "",
  "The flat-front box creates less drag overall": "",
  "Both create exactly the same amount of drag": "",
  "The rounded-front box creates less drag overall": "",
  "Neither shape experiences drag at highway speeds": "",
  "The rounded-front box allows air to flow more smoothly around it, creating less turbulence and less drag. Flat fronts push air abruptly, creating more turbulence and higher drag, which uses more fuel.": ""
}